" <!-- TC:TOPIC_PAGE -->",
" <div id=\"topicContent\">",
"  <div id=\"topicTitle\">",
"   Chapter 4D: Tamm-Horsfall mucoprotein",
"  </div>",
"  <div id=\"topicContributors\">",
"   <div>",
"    <a id=\"authors\">",
"    </a>",
"    <a class=\"contributor contributor_credentials contributorType\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/contributors\">",
"     Authors",
"    </a>",
"    <br/>",
"    <a class=\"contributor contributor_credentials\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/contributors\">",
"     Burton D Rose, MD",
"    </a>",
"    <br/>",
"    <a class=\"contributor contributor_credentials\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/contributors\">",
"     Theodore W Post, MD",
"    </a>",
"    <br/>",
"   </div>",
"   <div>",
"    <a class=\"contributor contributor_credentials contributorType\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/contributors\">",
"     Section Editor",
"    </a>",
"    <br/>",
"    <a class=\"contributor contributor_credentials\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/contributors\">",
"     Burton D Rose, MD",
"    </a>",
"    <br/>",
"   </div>",
"   <div>",
"    <a class=\"contributor contributor_credentials contributorType\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/contributors\">",
"     Deputy Editor",
"    </a>",
"    <br/>",
"    <a class=\"contributor contributor_credentials\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/contributors\">",
"     Theodore W Post, MD",
"    </a>",
"    <br/>",
"   </div>",
"  </div>",
"  <div id=\"disclosures\">",
"   <a href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/contributor-disclosure\" target=\"_blank\">",
"    Disclosures",
"   </a>",
"  </div>",
"  <div id=\"reviewProcess\">",
"   <span>",
"    All topics are updated as new evidence becomes available and our",
"   </span>",
"   <a href=\"/home/editorial-policy\" target=\"_blank\">",
"    peer review process",
"   </a>",
"   <span>",
"    is complete.",
"   </span>",
"  </div>",
"  <div id=\"literatureReviewDate\">",
"   <span class=\"emphasis\">",
"    Literature review current through:",
"   </span>",
"   Oct 2013.",
"   <span class=\"pipeSpace\">",
"    |",
"   </span>",
"   <span class=\"emphasis\">",
"    This topic last updated:",
"   </span>",
"   Apr 12, 2004.",
"  </div>",
"  <div id=\"topicText\">",
"   <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H1\">",
"    <span class=\"h1\">",
"     INTRODUCTION",
"    </span>",
"    &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;The thick ascending limb secretes a protein called Tamm-Horsfall mucoprotein (THMP) or uromodulin [",
"    <a class=\"abstract\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/abstract/1,2\">",
"     1,2",
"    </a>",
"    ]. THMP is a membrane protein that is principally located on the luminal surface of the cell membrane [",
"    <a class=\"abstract\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/abstract/3\">",
"     3",
"    </a>",
"    ].",
"   </p>",
"   <p>",
"    The function of THMP is unclear. It may have some immunomodulatory activity [",
"    <a class=\"abstract\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/abstract/1,2\">",
"     1,2",
"    </a>",
"    ] and may protect against urinary tract infection [",
"    <a class=\"abstract\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/abstract/4\">",
"     4",
"    </a>",
"    ]. THMP binds specifically to type 1 fimbriated Escherichia coli, the main cause of urinary tract infection, and may diminish adherence of the organism to the urothelium, an important step in the generation of infection [",
"    <a class=\"abstract\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/abstract/5\">",
"     5",
"    </a>",
"    ]. (See",
"    <a class=\"medical medical_review\" href=\"UTD.htm?15/46/16102?source=see_link\">",
"     \"Bacterial adherence and other virulence factors for urinary tract infection\"",
"    </a>",
"    .)",
"   </p>",
"   <p>",
"    THMP is important clinically because it represents the matrix of all urinary casts [",
"    <a class=\"abstract\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/abstract/6\">",
"     6",
"    </a>",
"    ]. The casts may contain only the matrix (hyaline casts) or can include degenerated cells or filtered proteins (granular casts), or intact cells that are present in the tubular fluid (red, white, or epithelial cell casts) [",
"    <a class=\"abstract\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/abstract/7\">",
"     7",
"    </a>",
"    ]. The type of cast that is present often has important diagnostic implications, e.g., red cell casts are virtually pathognomonic of glomerulonephritis or vasculitis. In contrast, hyaline or granular cast formation is not necessarily indicative of renal disease, since it can be seen in physiologic states such as exercise or fever [",
"    <a class=\"abstract\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/abstract/7\">",
"     7",
"    </a>",
"    ].",
"   </p>",
"   <p>",
"    THMP has been implicated in the pathogenesis of cast nephropathy, a form of renal failure associated with multiple myeloma in which dense intratubular casts occlude the flow of urine. Only some light chains appear to have this property, which seems to require coaggregation with THMP [",
"    <a class=\"abstract\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/abstract/8\">",
"     8",
"    </a>",
"    ]. (See",
"    <a class=\"medical medical_review\" href=\"UTD.htm?22/1/22551?source=see_link\">",
"     \"Pathogenesis and diagnosis of myeloma cast nephropathy (myeloma kidney)\"",
"    </a>",
"    .)",
"   </p>",
"   <p>",
"    Based upon positional clonal techniques, mutations in the gene that encodes for the THMP were found to underlie the following autosomal dominant disorders: typical familial juvenile hyperuricemic nephropathy and type 2 medullary cystic kidney disease [",
"    <a class=\"abstract\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/abstract/9,10\">",
"     9,10",
"    </a>",
"    ]. These two disorders, which are characterized by hyperuricemia, medullary cysts, interstitial nephritis, and progressive renal failure, are most likely variants of the same underlying physiologic disorder [",
"    <a class=\"abstract\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/abstract/10\">",
"     10",
"    </a>",
"    ]. Although speculative, these mutations probably disrupt the tertiary structure of the THMP, resulting in both disorders. (See",
"    <a class=\"medical medical_review\" href=\"UTD.htm?32/59/33721?source=see_link&amp;anchor=H2#H2\">",
"     \"Autosomal dominant interstitial kidney disease (medullary cystic kidney disease)\", section on 'Uromodulin-associated kidney disease (UAKD)'",
"    </a>",
"    .)",
"   </p>",
"   <p>",
"    It has also been suggested that THMP plays an etiologic role in other disease states such as the inflammatory response in interstitial nephritis. Tubular injury in this setting may lead to the release of THMP, which can then attract neutrophils by binding to specific receptors on the cell surface of the neutrophils [",
"    <a class=\"abstract\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/abstract/10,11\">",
"     10,11",
"    </a>",
"    ].",
"   </p>",
"   <p>",
"    (See",
"    <a class=\"medical medical_review\" href=\"UTD.htm?31/59/32694?source=see_link\">",
"     \"Chapter 5A: Distal tubule and connecting segment\"",
"    </a>",
"    .)",
"   </p>",
"   <p>",
"    (From Rose, BD, Post, TW, Clinical Physiology of Acid-Base and Electrolyte Disorders, 5th ed, McGraw-Hill, New York, 2001.)",
"   </p>",
"  </div>",
"  <div id=\"topicAgreement\">",
"   Use of UpToDate is subject to the",
"   <a class=\"licenseLink\" href=\"./license\" id=\"sla_in_page\" target=\"_blank\">",
"    Subscription and License Agreement",
"   </a>",
"   .",
"  </div>",
"  <div class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"references\">",
"   <h1>",
"    REFERENCES",
"   </h1>",
"   <ol id=\"reference\">",
"    <li>",
"     <a class=\"nounderline abstract\" href=\"UTD.htm?9/10/9378/abstract/1\">",
"      Kumar S, Muchmore A. Tamm-Horsfall protein--uromodulin (1950-1990). Kidney Int 1990; 37:1395.",
"     </a>",
"    </li>",
